  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions against money laundering:\n\n1. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n\n2. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- These are global standards for combating money laundering\n- Adopted by 37 member countries and multiple associate members\n\n3. Basel Convention\n- Provides guidelines for financial institutions to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n\n5. Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Facilitates international cooperation in combating money laundering\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring:\n- Banks to report suspicious transactions\n- Customer identification procedures\n- Record-keeping requirements\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Penalties for money laundering\n\nThe United States has specific laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act that address money laundering.\n\nThese laws aim to:\n- Detect and prevent criminal financial activities\n- Track potential terrorist financing\n- Ensure transparency in financial transactions\n- Prosecute individuals and organizations involved in money laundering\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment.",
